description.text:
This adapter bracket allows the mounting of an MKS SBASE control board to an MKS GEN screw hole pattern.  I created this bracket to easily mount an SBASE on my Prusa i3 frame without the need to drill new holes.
To assemble:
Press 3mm nuts into the four retainers, these are used to fasten the adapter to your chassis.  
Mount the SBASE to the bracket using 3mm or 4-40 screws and be careful not to over tighten since they are simply threaded into the plastic bosses.  
Mount the assembly to your chassis with 3mm screws.  NOTE: Be careful not to use screws that are too long or they will hit the back of the SBASE PCB!  I printed 4mm spacers to allow for longer screws and provide additional air flow behind the SBASE.

For our project we created a plane. We call the plane LDC. The plane is a quick and elusive plane. The plane’s long wings gives it quick speed and it allows it to glide across through the air with ease. There are 3 grids, one at the end of each wing, and one on the top. Project
• Objectives
-Learn how to create objects using Blender.
-Learn how to 3-D print objects created. • Audiences
-Middle schoolers and up would be the most appropriate audience for this project. • Preparation
-Know how to use a computer.
-Download Blender to computer. • Results
-We designed a plane.

STEPS
  • Turn cube to rectangle (6 units by 2 units).
  • Add grid (8 units by 3 units). Put in the center of rectangle to form the wings.
  • Add cone. Put on the front of the rectangle.
  • Add grid. Put upright at the end of wing of plane.
  • Duplicate (shift + D) the grid and put it on the other wing.
  • Duplicate the grid and place it at an angle on the top of the plane towards the back.
  • Add 2 cylinder pole under wings for support.

description.text: Our Project Is an abstract "paperweight" if you will, designed just for ascetic pleasure. We didn't have any real inspiration, but we just let out imagination fly. The cool thing about this is that it is open to interpretation. Some people see it as a bird, others as just some abstract piece of art, others something totally different. That is why we like about our unique, one-of-a-kind, project.

As we said earlier, our project had no defined inspiration, so if you try to recreate this you really can't mess up. We just started with a shape, then changed, edited, and manipulated it to look the way we wanted it to. First, start with a shape and edit the vertices, edges, and faces until it is manipulated to the desired form.

Objectives Student will learn team working skills as well as basic knowledge of how to run Blender. Students will also learn about 3D printing and the tech involved. Audience We believe students should be at least 13 due to the steep learning curve of blender and the challenge of making their project come out of the program. Preparation Students should watch a tutorial on YouTube about creating a simple object. It will greatly expand one's ability to create and edit one's own project. It will undoubtedly be expected for a computer and a 3D modeling program to start one's own project. Do or do not, there is no try. Steps This project was based on an inspiration less idea. Random parts of an ico sphere were shrunk and other random parts were moved to a random location. However, after a few minutes a bird was barely recognizable. We tried to design the project to model a bird after that moment. We used the edit mode and the wireframe extensively during the editing of this project. Results Students shouldn't be graded on what they build, because that is purely objective, but on how they work to design, create, and perfect their build, and if they gave their full effort.

Printing this size, they almost always work for us; printing a scaled-down version requiring about twice as high positioning accuracy fails much more often, primarily depending on filament variations. comments.text: I'm not sure what you mean by "lighter" -- I usually print things like this with 2 bottom shells. For anything this flat, I generally print PLA directly on the 70C glass of our M2. By the time the bed has cooled to 35C or so, the object typically detaches itself. Printing this on blue tape, which I use for parts with small footprints, it could be a nightmare to get it off the bed. In any case, if it sticks, I'd recommend using a razor blade in a safety holder to slip under the part.
comments.author: owens

comments.text: Our prints detach from the bed just fine; that's not the issue. Most people print their first layer with a higher extrusion width, to improve adhesion and make a solid base for the print. Slic3r, for example, defaults to making the first layer twice as wide as the layer height, with the higher layers narrower. Because of that, the gaps between the hinges were closed up on the first layer when we printed them. I was suggesting that your library could allow for that, so that the prints would be more likely to work for a printer other than your personal one. But of course that's entirely up to you, and if you do choose to release your library, someone else can always make that change.

I've been printing a lot of camera parts, and the imprecision introduced by a significantly fatter first-layer diameter with Slic3r was not ok. I adjust the bed and run the first layer at (roughly) the same diameter extrusion, and usually get watertight first layers.

This supercapacitor powered, 3d printed, motorized rotating ornament has Engineer written all over it. Rudolph, riding in an airplane, pulls Santa round and round in this "not available in stores" device. https://youtu.be/2o5ZmTBL7L0 Print the various pieces.
Paint Santa and the Reindeer.
Remove the female end of a servo extension cable and solder two of the wires to the gear motor.
Insert the motor in the motor holder.
Glue the motor holder to the "ring with base."
Glue the "shaft connector" to the "flying bar."
Insert the shaft connector onto the motor shaft.
Remove the male end of a servo extension cable and connect two wires to the supercapacitor (or battery).
Plug the power cable and motor cables together and the ornament will run. The supercapacitor (though it has a lot of farads) is rated for .4 watt hours of energy storage (that's less than half of what an AAA battery stores). The capacitor can be recharged in a minute or less (depending on the power supply attached) and can be recharged over 500,000 times. The ornament will run for about eight hours on a single charge. Santa and the reindeer plane were created using clay by my wife, Annelle. They were scanned with a MakerBot Digitizer and combined with 123d designs using TinkerCad.

description.text: The project was really open, we had to design something that would beneficial to the school environment and would be able to adapt easily. SJ.HT.NW 3rd period
Basic Shapes are what get you through to make something bigger. Scaling doesn't make your shape any bigger in a printing software.

Objectives The student will learn to successfully use blender and print a 3D model. Audiences The expected audience to do this project is Advanced Upper Middle School to at least Upper College. Preparation The student doesn't necessarily need any background knowledge to do this project, but a lesson before hand really would help. The materials that would be needed to do this project are a 3D Printer, a printing software, a laptop, a computer mouse, and if many people are going to use the same laptop you would need a flash drive. Steps! The steps that we took to make this project are:
We started with a cube then we altered the scaling to make it a rectangle. After we had made it the dimensions that we wanted, we extruded out the center to make it like a picture frame. Then we made sure it was in object mode then we added a cylinder scaled it to the way we wanted it then duplicated it, we could only move it the X, Y, and Z axis or it would mess everything up. after that we went back to basic shapes and to a sphere and cute it half by using control and left click on the mouse then click delete not backspace and faces and the edges. Then drag the half sphere up to the bottom of the cylinder. You are now done! Results After this project each student should know how to operate blender and should have successfully printed a 3D model from the printer. As a group we believe we should be graded on how well operated blender and our effort for trying.

Notes: No need for any support, as prints face down without problems. Used 0.4mm nozzle, 2.85mm Dutch Orange Colorfabb filament, at 210C and 50mm speed.

Method of attachment Turn off power to Ultimaker original. Unplug. Undo the 3mm hex bolts from the old wooden Uti controller box. Label the two grey cables that connect it to the main controller. Push these grey cables back through the hole in the floor of the Ultimaker, so they appear underneath. Re insert the cables as you marked them. Using 4x5mm hex bolts secure the uni controller to the print, and be careful not to tighten too much. Line up new panel on front of Ultimaker box and mark for the 3 retaining 12mm Hex bolts, drill and secure with washers and nuts . I use the Panelolu2 knob remix as it suits the new panel, and used a small paper shim to get a tight fit. Now turn on Ultimaker and there you have a new 45degree controller unit that looks aa lot better then the old wooden one. ( sorry Ultimaker, but the wooden one is naff)

Old one got on my nerves and all uni-controller boxes on thingiverse, not practical. Designed in 123D design, and allows for a 45degree lift, two slots for SD cards and unblocks the front of the Ultimaker original. And perfect fit for the Ultimaker Uti-controller.

Simcha Davis's CNC cut furniture with historic traditions.

This project has a total has a total of 11 pieces, each of which are one or two inches thick, all of which fit together and are varied in thickness (either 1 inch thick or 2 inches thick). It is very important to measure the exact thickness of each piece of wood. Because we did not plane both sides of the planks, it created some variation in thickness. We had to account for this by measuring everything; it was imperative that all the cut-outs were precise, so that the pieces would fit together properly.   
Once the settings for the file were complete, we screwed onto the bed of the router all of the pieces of wood to be routed. Because we were making 12 benches, we made a jig. (Although our jig was not very effective, I highly suggest using one if you make multiple benches.) In addition to the varying thickness, the wood was often warped, which created a huge problem. The drill bit often was unable to cut through the entire piece of wood because it was not long enough.   
Initially, we used a quarter-inch upcut drill bit that was three inches long, but it did not leave the wiggle room necessary to accommodate the varying wood thicknesses, height, and the issue of warping. After much trial and error and a few broken drill bits, we switched to a straight half-inch upcut drill bit that was four inches long. The half-inch drill bit is what should be used when cutting this file, especially if you are using material that is two inches thick. Once we switched to this drill bit, the file was much easier to cut and it took much less time. The only problem was that because the bit is so heavy, it kept falling out of the collet. To avoid this problem, make sure that you are using a brand-new collet, so the bit is very secure.   
This file depends heavily on measurement for material thickness. If you are cutting this file multiple times, keep measuring and adjusting the pieces.   
It should be noted that the zig-zag pieces for the seat of the bench and table are not an exact fit. They fit together well, with a few tiny gaps between the teeth of the zig-zag. If this isn'Ât the aesthetic you are going for, the points should be simple enough to adjust in the file to make them fit perfectly.

description.text: Here's a version of mracole's Sonic Screwdriver, cracked into piece for multi-color printing. You may need to resize the support rod for best fit with your parts.

Revision: Added a new optional revised version of the ring with clips and the switch body that will likely be a bit stronger and more robust. The switch can be printed in grey and glued into the switch body.
Re-Revision: After trying to print the new revision of the ring with clips and continually failing, I've added a reinforced version that adds some support between the rings and the clips. It sacrifices a bit of the look for something that should print far better.

Printer:

Monoprice

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.1

Infill:

Take Your Pick

Notes: Print one of each file, in the following color schemes:



Blue

Sonic - 001 - Crystal.stl

Sonic - 004 - Switch Body.stl

Sonic - 007 - Cap.stl



Gold/Yellow

Sonic - 003 - Gold Ring.stl

Sonic - 005 - Bottom Rings with Insert.stl



Silver/Grey

Sonic - 002 - Silver Ring with Clips.stl

Sonic - 006 - Lower Handle.stl



The Silver Ring with Clips will likely need supports to print, the lower handle may print better with them as well.



I printed the entire model with rafts for better quality, though they're likely unneeded for most parts.



For better stability (and because I'm new at ABS) I epoxied the sides of the clips to the switch body. YMMV. Good luck! Make it Fantastic! Allonz-y! Geronimo!

comments.text: No experimentation with other fans. Re slot size: I had a gut feeling that the air pressure is higher at the fan side of the exit slot, and the pressure is lower at the far side.
